This turns out to be due to the assistive MathML that is added inside the `mjx-container` element.  In Safari (which doesn't have very good support for MathML) and Chrome (which has none at all), the assistive MathML was wider than the typeset math (due primarily to the backspacing that is being done to get the letters to touch properly).  That was making the container have greater width than the typeset math itself, causing the scroll bar.

One work-around would be to add

``` css
mjx-assistive-mml {
  max-width: 100%;
}
```

which should make cause the assistive MathML to limit its width to that of the typeset math.

